              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">What is the efficient market hypothesis?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.longandshort.com/email/images/ls-jan-6-3.jpg" alt="Foundation" href="https://www.longandshort.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">The efficient market hypothesis (EMH) is a foundational theory in finance that asserts all available information about a security is reflected in its price at any given time. EMH implies that markets are "efficient," making it impossible to consistently outperform them through stock selection or market timing.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          There are three forms of EMH: weak, semi-strong, and strong. The weak form suggests past price movements can't predict future prices, while the semi-strong form states prices instantly incorporate all public information. The strong form goes further, claiming even insider information is already factored in.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          For investors, EMH challenges active management strategies, favoring passive approaches like index funds. However, critics argue behavioral biases and market anomalies, like bubbles, contradict EMH.</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
